ce cultural landscape, the study investigates a hitherto unexamined debate that was at the heart of state building in Buenos Aires. It simultaneously challenges traditional male-centred accounts of the period and serves as a counterpoint to historic feministapproaches to print culture. IONA MACINTYRE lectures in Hispanic Studies at the University of Edinburgh.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminismxHistoryzArgentinazBuenos Aires. 0aLiterature and societyzArgentinazBuenos Aires. 0aPopular culturezArgentinazBuenos Aires. 0aWomen in literature. 0aWomenxHistoryzArgentinazBuenos Aires. 4aHispanic Studies. 4aModern Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aBooks.  aBuenos Aires.  aFeminism.  aGender.  aIndependence Movement in Latin America.  aLatin American History.  aLatin American culture.  aLatin American gender.  aNineteenth Century.  aPopular literature.  aPress.  aThe Woman Question.  aWomen's studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846158094?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846158094423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846158094/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles